3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In [13]:
ax = sns.countplot(x = 'Gender', data = data)

for bars in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(bars)
In [14]:
sales_gen = data.groupby(['Gender'], as_index = False)['Amount'].sum().sort_values(by = 'Amount', ascending = False)
sns.barplot(x = 'Gender', y = "Amount", data = sales_gen)
Out[14]:
<Axes: xlabel='Gender', ylabel='Amount'>
From above graph we can see that most of the buyers are female and even the purchasing power of females greater than men¶
In [15]:

for bars in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(bars)

In [22]:
# Total amount vs Age group
sales_age = data.groupby(["Age Group"], as_index = False)["Amount"].sum().sort_values(by = "Amount", ascending = False)

sns.barplot(x = "Age Group", y = "Amount", data = sales_age)
Out[22]:
<Axes: xlabel='Age Group', ylabel='Amount'>
From above graph we can see that most of the buyers are of age group between 26-35 years. (women)¶
In [35]:
# Total number of orders from top 10 states
sales_state = data.groupby(["State"], as_index = False)["Orders"].sum().sort_values(by = "Orders", ascending = False).head(10)

sns.set(rc={"figure.figsize" : (15, 5)})
sns.barplot(data = sales_state, x = "State", y = "Orders")
Out[35]:
<Axes: xlabel='State', ylabel='Orders'>
In [37]:
# total amount from top 10 states
amount_state = data.groupby(["State"], as_index = False)["Amount"].sum().sort_values(by = "Amount", ascending = False).head(10)

sns.set(rc={"figure.figsize" : (15, 5)})
sns.barplot(data = amount_state, x = "State", y = "Amount")
Out[37]:
<Axes: xlabel='State', ylabel='Amount'>
From above graph we can see that most of the orders are from UP, Maharashtra & Karnataka respectively.¶
